   "source": "# Session 03c — image-only pia surface with onset-feature scoring\n\n**Date.**  2026-04-19 → 2026-04-20 (iter 5–6 added)\n\n**Goal.**  Close the one remaining image-only pia failure (755252, autofluorescence-limited) by extracting intensity features at the N22 \"truth\" surface and building a classifier / selection rule that uses them.  Constraint: the final rule must run on the image alone — centroid data is for validation only.\n\n**Starting point.**  The v2.1 image-based estimator in `03_image_based_surface.py` matched N22 on 5/6 HCR subjects; on 755252 it landed in a thick autofluorescence sheet ~200 µm above the real pia, producing onset = 62.5 µm (target ≤ 10 µm).\n\n**Endpoint.**  New public API (`score_surface_quality`, `auto_select_surface` in `03_image_based_surface.py`; convenience wrapper `estimate_pia_surface_image_autoselect` in `benchmark_analysis.py`) matches N22 onset quality on **all 6** HCR subjects including 755252.  The fix is a *selection* over a small candidate bank, not a new fitter.  Scoring is **OOT-aware** (iter 6): in-tissue columns only.  On this 6-subject HCR benchmark the mask effect is small — under the robust reference `np.percentile(colmax, 99.5)` only 0–9 of 400 grid columns are OOT per subject.  Iter 5's \"52–94 % OOT\" headline was a reference-inflation artefact from using `vol.max()` as the global reference; the correct reference avoids single-voxel saturation bias and makes scoring robust on subjects with bright artefacts (788406, 790322).\n\n---\n\n## The 6-iteration arc\n\n| # | question | result | artefact |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| 1 | Can a per-column intensity feature at z = N22 separate true pia from v2.1's AF-surface on 755252? | Yes — `below_near` (mean intensity in a 40 µm slab below z) is **0.052 at N22 vs 0.000 at v2.1** on 755252, cleanly distinguishing the two; 5× to 50× smaller gap on clean subjects. | `iterations/iter01_*` |\n| 2 | Can we use `below_near` to filter per-column tops *inside* v2.1's Stage-3 so the fitter avoids AF-contaminated tops? | **No** — per-top `below_near` is not separable between AF tops and pia tops.  The iter-1 signal came from evaluating the feature at the fitted *surface z*, not at individual tops.  Per-top filtering is a dead end. | `iterations/iter02_*` |\n| 3 | Can we score **whole candidate surfaces** (different channel subsets × `target_quantile`) by `below_near` and pick the best? | Almost — raw Q selects the 755252 fix correctly, but fails on 767018 where a surface deep inside tissue body has even higher `below_near`.  Fix: add a contrast term `Qcon_n = median((below-above)/(below+above+ε))` that is ≈ 1 at pia, ≈ 0 in the AF-to-pia gap, and 0.1–0.55 deep in tissue.  Rule `argmax Q s.t. Qcon_n ≥ 0.9` picks a valid pia candidate on **all 6** subjects. | `iterations/iter03_*` |\n| 4 | Does the selection rule work via the proper API (not inline scripting)? | Yes — added `score_surface_quality` + `auto_select_surface` to the image module and `estimate_pia_surface_image_autoselect` to the benchmark API.  Re-ran on all 6 subjects and selections match iter-3 exactly. | `iterations/iter04_*` |\n| 5 | Do the fitted surfaces actually sit on the pia when overlaid on raw volume slices?  And how much of the 20×20 scoring grid lies in out-of-tissue regions? | Surfaces overlay correctly on all 6 subjects.  OOT audit reported 52–94 %, *but this turned out to be an artefact* — using `vol.max()` as the \"global max\" reference is dominated by saturated voxels on HCR (`vol.max()` is 32–253× a typical bright column), so the 5 % threshold was inflated above most real tissue columns.  Iter 6 fixes the reference. | `iterations/iter05_*` |\n| 6 | Fix the reference so the OOT mask is meaningful; confirm selections. | `score_surface_quality` now defaults to `min_col_max_frac = 0.05` with `global_max = np.percentile(colmax, 99.5)` (robust to single-voxel saturation, samples a typical bright *column*).  `auto_select_surface` shares the `global_max` across the bank so the mask is identical for all candidates.  Under the robust reference the 15 %-padded interior grid is mostly all-tissue (0–9/400 OOT per subject).  Selections are unchanged from iter 4 on 6/6 subjects.  Main practical win: scoring no longer blows up on saturated-voxel volumes. | `iterations/iter06_*` |\n"
