   "source": "## OOT handling — top-down grid view (iter 6)\n\nTop-down (XY) view of column-max intensity for each subject.  White dashed contour = 5 % of `np.percentile(colmax, 99.5)` (the tissue/OOT cutoff).  Green dots = grid columns kept for scoring; red dots = OOT columns, dropped.  Numbers per subject (out of 400 grid points):\n\n| subject | in-tissue | OOT | global-max ref (p99.5 of colmax) |\n|---|---:|---:|---:|\n| 755252 | 400 | 0 | 8.05 |\n| 767018 | 400 | 0 | 4.79 |\n| 767022 | 398 | 2 | 8.76 |\n| 782149 | 391 | 9 | 6.00 |\n| 788406 | 400 | 0 | 4.71 |\n| 790322 | 400 | 0 | 5.57 |\n\nTwo notes:\n\n1. **Iter 5's \"52–94 % OOT\" was a reference bug.**  The iter 5 audit used `colmax.max() = vol.max()` as its global-max reference.  On HCR `load_hcr_combined` the combined volume occasionally has saturated voxels that read 32–253× brighter than a typical tissue column, so `5 % × vol.max()` landed above most real columns.  Replacing the reference with `np.percentile(colmax, 99.5)` — robust to single-pixel saturation and sampling the correct scale (a bright *column*, not a bright *voxel*) — drops the OOT frac to 0–2.25 %.\n2. **The fix is still worth having.**  `vol.max()` as a reference would flag 100 % of 788406 and 99.75 % of 790322 as OOT (we saw this while iterating) and produce `All-NaN slice encountered` on medians.  The robust reference prevents that class of crash.  Bottom-OOT (padded zeros below the tissue) doesn't need a separate mask — a surface below the tissue produces `Qcon_n ≈ -1` and is rejected by the contrast gate."
