   "source": "## How to use\n\n```python\nfrom benchmark_data_loader import load_subject\nfrom benchmark_analysis import estimate_pia_surface_image_autoselect\n\ns = load_subject('755252')\nsurface, info, scores = estimate_pia_surface_image_autoselect(s)\n\n# surface  → quadratic dict {a, b, c, p, q, r, ...}\n# info     → {'selected': 'mid488_tq0.85', 'used_channels': ['488', '514'], ...}\n# scores   → DataFrame of all candidates with Q / Qcon_n / pass / selected\n```\n\n## Key design notes & caveats\n\n- **Why two metrics.**  `Q` (median below-surface brightness) discriminates pia from gap but fails to reject deep-in-tissue surfaces.  `Qcon_n` (normalised above/below contrast) rejects deep surfaces but cannot rank real-pia candidates.  Their combination is both necessary and sufficient on 6 subjects.\n- **OOT-aware scoring.**  Both metrics are computed over *in-tissue* grid columns only (`col.max() ≥ 5 % × np.percentile(colmax, 99.5)`).  On this HCR benchmark 0–9 / 400 columns are dropped per subject (the 15 %-padded interior grid is mostly all-tissue).  The mask exists mainly as a safety net — without a robust `global_max` reference, saturated voxels can drag every real column below the threshold and cause `All-NaN` crashes.  Bottom-OOT (padded zeros below the tissue) is handled by the `Qcon_n ≥ 0.9` gate (below-tissue surfaces read Qcon_n ≈ -1) — no extra check needed.\n- **Why `np.percentile(colmax, 99.5)` and not `vol.max()` or `np.percentile(vol, 99.5)`.**  `vol.max()` is dominated by a handful of saturated voxels (32–253× typical on HCR `load_hcr_combined`).  `percentile(vol, 99.5)` over the >1 B voxels of a level-4 volume is a \"typical bright voxel\" (~0.3), not a \"bright column\" (~1.0), so 5 % of it passes every column including truly empty ones.  `percentile(colmax, 99.5)` is robust to saturation (each column contributes at most one bright-pixel's worth) and samples the correct scale.\n- **Distribution-driven threshold.**  The 0.9 cut on `Qcon_n` was chosen because on this 6-subject benchmark real-pia candidates land at ≥ 0.98 and tissue-body candidates at ≤ 0.55 — a > 0.4 gap with no candidates in between.  Any threshold in [0.6, 0.97] would produce identical selections; 0.9 is the centre of the valley.  If future data lives in that gap, the threshold should be re-picked from the bimodal distribution (per the session-global rule on thresholds).\n- **Soft bias toward deeper pia.**  `argmax Q` prefers the deepest candidate among pia-pass survivors because tissue brightness monotonically increases with depth in the 10–50 µm window.  On 790322 this nudges the selection ~16 µm below N22 (above_frac 1.13 % instead of 0.07 %).  Still well within gates, but worth noting if we later demand tighter control (e.g. GFP surfaces).\n- **AF-carrying channels are subject-specific.**  The \"right\" channel subset varies: 755252 wants `488+514` (drop AF-heavy 405 & 594), 767018 wants `594-only`, 782149/788406 want `488+mid+594` (drop 405).  Auto-select handles this without needing per-subject hand-tuning.\n\n## References\n\n- Iteration logs with per-iteration details: [log.md](log.md).\n- Individual iteration notebooks: [iter01](iterations/iter01_analysis.ipynb) · [iter02](iterations/iter02_analysis.ipynb) · [iter03](iterations/iter03_analysis.ipynb) · [iter04](iterations/iter04_analysis.ipynb) · [iter06](iterations/iter06_analysis.ipynb).\n- Public API lives in `code/dev_code/03_image_based_surface.py` and `code/dev_code/benchmark_analysis.py`."
